# Chief Justice of Canada

The [Chief Justice of Canada](/Chief_Justice_of_Canada) (French: *juge en chef du Canada*) holds the singular distinction of being the presiding judge over the nine-member [Supreme Court of Canada](/Supreme_Court_of_Canada), which stands as the highest [judicial](/Judiciary) body across all of [Canada](/Canada). This position, therefore, inherently designates the Chief Justice as the highest-ranking judge within the entire intricate [Canadian court system](/Court_system_of_Canada), a fact that seems to weigh heavily on the very fabric of the nation's legal landscape.

As outlined by the foundational [Supreme Court Act](/Supreme_Court_Act), the Chief Justice is designated as a [Crown in Council](/King-in-Council) appointment. This means the selection is made by the [Crown](/The_Crown) acting directly on the considered advice of the sitting [prime minister](/Prime_Minister_of_Canada) and the [minister of justice](/Minister_of_Justice_and_Attorney_General_of_Canada). It's a process that ensures a certain political alignment, or at least a lack of overt opposition, for such a crucial role. Once appointed, the Chief Justice's tenure continues without a fixed term length, ending only upon their resignation, reaching the mandatory retirement age of 75 years, death, or, in the rarest of circumstances, removal from office for cause—a measure reserved for the most egregious breaches of conduct. By a long-standing, almost unbreakable tradition, a new Chief Justice is almost invariably selected from among the Court's existing [incumbent](/Incumbent) [puisne justices](/Puisne_justice), ensuring continuity and a deep understanding of the Court's internal workings, which one might argue is simply the path of least resistance.

Beyond merely presiding, the Chief Justice wields a significant, almost gravitational, influence over the [procedural rules of the Court](/Procedures_of_the_Supreme_Court_of_Canada), shaping how justice is administered and how cases are heard. They hold the central position during [oral arguments](/Oral_arguments), guiding the flow of legal discourse, and are expected to lead the often-complex and sometimes contentious discussions of cases among the other justices. Furthermore, the role extends far beyond the courtroom's immediate confines. The Chief Justice also serves as the [deputy governor general](/Deputy_of_the_Governor_General_of_Canada), a temporary and often inconvenient stand-in for the viceregal office. They are the [ex-officio](/Ex-officio) chairman of the influential [Canadian Judicial Council](/Canadian_Judicial_Council), a body tasked with upholding judicial standards, and they preside over the committee responsible for selecting recipients of the prestigious [Order of Canada](/Order_of_Canada). In moments of national exigency, a Chief Justice is also prepared to assume the extraordinary role of [Administrator of Canada](/Administrator_(Canada)), exercising the full viceregal duties of the governor general should that office become vacant due to death, resignation, or incapacitation, a testament to the unforeseen burdens the position can entail.

Currently, the weighty mantle of Chief Justice of Canada is borne by [Richard Wagner](/Richard_Wagner_(judge)), who assumed the role on December 18, 2017. Since the Supreme Court's inception in 1875, a total of 18 individuals have held this paramount judicial position. The very first to navigate the nascent waters of this office was [William Buell Richards](/William_Buell_Richards). Notably, [Beverley McLachlin](/Beverley_McLachlin) holds the record as the longest-serving Canadian Chief Justice, having served for an impressive 17 years and 341 days, and she was also the first woman to ever ascend to this powerful and historically male-dominated position, a rather belated but significant step.

## History

The formal establishment of the [Supreme Court of Canada](/Supreme_Court_of_Canada) commenced with the solemn administration of the [oath of office](/Oath_of_office) to its inaugural Chief Justice, [William Buell Richards](/William_Buell_Richards), on October 8, 1875, a ceremony overseen by General [William O'Grady Haly](/William_O%27Grady_Haly). A month later, on November 8, the five initial puisne justices followed suit, taking their own oaths and completing the foundational composition of the Court. This was not without its early political machinations; in January 1879, Chief Justice Richards found himself in a position where resignation became the only viable path forward. This decision was reportedly influenced by persistent pressure from his long-time friend and political ally, Prime Minister [John A. Macdonald](/John_A._Macdonald), a situation likely exacerbated by Richards' declining health, which, as history often shows, provides a convenient justification for political maneuverings. Subsequently, on January 11, 1879, [William Johnstone Ritchie](/William_Johnstone_Ritchie) was appointed as the new Chief Justice by Macdonald, a swift transition that underscored the Prime Minister's firm hand in judicial appointments.

Tragedy struck on September 25, 1892, when Chief Justice [William Johnstone Ritchie](/William_Johnstone_Ritchie) passed away at the age of 78, succumbing to a relapse of bronchitis. His death immediately triggered speculation regarding his successor. Early whispers and rumors in political circles suggested that the then-Prime Minister [John Abbott](/John_Abbott) might consider appointing Justice Minister [John Sparrow David Thompson](/John_Sparrow_David_Thompson) directly to the top judicial post. However, a strong and widely held opinion existed within the legal and political communities that the Chief Justice position should not automatically default to the longest-serving member of the Court, a sentiment vigorously opposed by prominent Conservative senator [James Robert Gowan](/James_Robert_Gowan), who was a key party advisor on legal affairs. Senator Gowan, expressing his reservations, even went so far as to write to Justice Minister Thompson, suggesting that Justice Strong be allowed to retire to avoid his potential appointment and that the entire process be delayed, candidly indicating his distinct lack of faith in Strong's work ethic and commitment to the role. Despite these internal doubts and considerable lobbying, just three weeks after assuming the premiership himself, Prime Minister Thompson ultimately appointed [Samuel Henry Strong](/Samuel_Henry_Strong) as the Court's third Chief Justice, demonstrating that political will often trumps advice, no matter how well-intentioned.

A significant, if somewhat bureaucratic, change occurred in April 1896. During the tenure of the Conservative government under Prime Minister [Mackenzie Bowell](/Mackenzie_Bowell), the [7th Canadian Parliament](/7th_Canadian_Parliament) passed an amendment to the Supreme and Exchequer Courts Act. This legislative alteration formally established the title of "Chief Justice of Canada." Prior to this amendment, the highest judicial officer was simply referred to as "chief justice," a distinction that, while seemingly minor, officially cemented the national scope and singular authority of the position. It was a formalization that reflected the growing maturity and self-awareness of the Canadian legal system.

## Appointment

The appointment process for the Chief Justice is meticulously governed by the [Supreme Court Act](/Supreme_Court_Act), with the selection made by the [Governor in Council](/King-in-Council) acting squarely on the advice of the [prime minister](/Prime_Minister_of_Canada). This seemingly straightforward process is, of course, underpinned by specific constitutional requirements. Under this component of the [Constitution of Canada](/Constitution_of_Canada), any judge appointed to the Supreme Court, and by extension the Chief Justice, must meet stringent qualifications: they must either be "a judge of a superior court of a province or a barrister or advocate of at least ten years standing at the bar of a province." One might cynically observe that a decade of legal practice is merely the bare minimum for navigating the labyrinthine complexities of Canadian law.

A deeply entrenched, though not strictly codified, tradition dictates that the Chief Justice is appointed from among the ranks of the Court's existing puisne judges. In the entire [history of the Court](/History_of_the_Supreme_Court_of_Canada), this tradition has been breached only twice: with the very first Chief Justice, [William Buell Richards](/William_Buell_Richards), and later with [Charles Fitzpatrick](/Charles_Fitzpatrick), both of whom were appointed directly without prior service as puisne justices. Furthermore, another customary practice dictates an alternating selection process: the Chief Justice is typically chosen alternately from either the three justices who, by law, must hail from [Quebec](/Quebec) (representing its unique [civil law](/Law_in_Quebec) system) or from the other six justices drawn from the rest of Canada (who embody the [common law](/Law_of_Canada) tradition). This delicate balance, designed to reflect Canada's dual legal heritage, has only been broken once since 1933, when [Brian Dickson](/Brian_Dickson) of [Manitoba](/Manitoba) was appointed to succeed [Bora Laskin](/Bora_Laskin) of [Ontario](/Ontario) in 1984, a rare deviation that nonetheless passed without significant constitutional uproar, perhaps because the legal system, much like the universe, tends towards entropy.

## Duties

The most visible and central duty of the Chief Justice is, without question, to preside over all hearings before the [Supreme Court](/Supreme_Court_of_Canada). During these proceedings, the Chief Justice occupies the central chair, a symbolic and literal focal point of the Court's authority. Should the Chief Justice be, for whatever reason, unavailable or absent, the weighty responsibility of presiding falls to the senior puisne judge, ensuring the uninterrupted flow of justice.

### Judicial Council

Beyond the immediate courtroom, the Chief Justice also chairs the [Canadian Judicial Council](/Canadian_Judicial_Council), a significant body that encompasses all chief justices and associate chief justices of superior courts throughout Canada. Established in 1971 by the Judges Act, this council performs several critical functions. It organizes essential seminars for federally appointed judges, fostering continuous legal education and professional development. It also serves as a vital forum for coordinating discussions on issues of concern to the judiciary, allowing for a unified approach to systemic challenges. Crucially, the Council is empowered to conduct inquiries into the conduct of any federally appointed judge, whether initiated by a public complaint or at the specific request of a federal or provincial minister of justice or attorney general. This oversight mechanism is designed to maintain public confidence in the integrity of the judiciary, a task that, given human nature, is perpetually ongoing.

### Other duties

Before taking the judicial [oath of office](/Oath_of_office), the Chief Justice is first sworn in as a member of the [Privy Council](/Queen%27s_Privy_Council_for_Canada), an exclusive circle that underscores the deep connection between the judiciary and the executive branch, however ceremonial it might appear. Furthermore, the Chief Justice holds a seat on the advisory council of Canada's highest civilian honour, the [Order of Canada](/Order_of_Canada). In a display of judicial prudence, or perhaps simply an aversion to unnecessary complications, the Chief Justice traditionally abstains from voting on a candidate's [removal from the order](/Removal_from_the_Order_of_Canada). This practice is rooted in a pragmatic concern: such removal processes have, to date, primarily applied to individuals convicted of criminal offences in lower courts. Should such an individual appeal their conviction all the way to the Supreme Court, the Chief Justice's prior involvement in a removal decision could, quite rightly, create an awkward and ethically compromising conflict of interest.

Additionally, under the provisions of the [Electoral Boundaries Readjustment Act](/Electoral_Boundaries_Readjustment_Act), each province is mandated to establish a three-person commission tasked with the politically sensitive process of modifying that province's federal [ridings](/Electoral_district_(Canada)). While the chair of each such commission is typically appointed by the chief justice of that specific province, if no such appointment is made, the responsibility, like an unwanted inheritance, falls to the Chief Justice of Canada, ensuring that the process, however reluctantly, moves forward.

## Administrator of Canada

The very fabric of Canada's constitutional framework anticipates moments when the highest office might be temporarily vacant or incapacitated. The [Constitution Act, 1867](/Constitution_Act,_1867) explicitly provides for the possibility of an "Administrator for the Time being carrying on the Government of Canada," a safeguard against a vacuum of power. These provisions are further elaborated in the [Letters Patent, 1947](/Letters_Patent,_1947), which delineate the precise mechanisms respecting the Office of [Governor General](/Governor_General_of_Canada). Specifically, should the governor general die, become incapacitated, or be absent from the country for a period exceeding one month, the Chief Justice—or, if that office itself is vacant, the senior puisne justice of the Supreme Court—is automatically designated as the [Administrator of Canada](/Administrator_(Canada)). In this capacity, they are empowered to exercise all the powers and duties typically held by the governor general, a responsibility that shifts them from the pinnacle of judicial authority to the temporary apex of executive and ceremonial power.

This viceregal role has been invoked on four distinct occasions throughout Canadian history, each instance underscoring the critical importance of this constitutional failsafe. Chief Justice [Lyman Duff](/Lyman_Duff) served as Administrator in 1940, and Chief Justice [Robert Taschereau](/Robert_Taschereau) did so in 1967, both following the unfortunate deaths in office of the incumbent governors general. More recently, Chief Justice [Beverley McLachlin](/Beverley_McLachlin) stepped into the role in July 2005 when the Governor General underwent surgery, a testament to the fact that even modern medical procedures can trigger constitutional contingencies. The most recent instance occurred following the resignation of [Julie Payette](/Julie_Payette) in January 2021, at which point [Richard Wagner](/Richard_Wagner_(judge)) assumed the duties of Administrator until the formal appointment of [Mary Simon](/Mary_Simon) as governor general in July of the same year. It's a role that demands adaptability, thrusting a jurist into a realm of statecraft they might prefer to merely observe.

Beyond these extraordinary circumstances, the Chief Justice, along with the other justices of the Supreme Court, routinely serve as [deputies of the governor general](/Deputy_of_the_Governor_General_of_Canada) for more mundane, yet equally crucial, functions. These include the solemn act of giving [Royal Assent](/Royal_Assent) to bills that have successfully navigated the legislative complexities of [Parliament](/Parliament_of_Canada), the signing of various official documents that underpin the machinery of government, and the ceremonial reception of credentials from newly appointed [high commissioners](/High_Commissioner) and [ambassadors](/Ambassador), a diplomatic dance that ensures the continuity of international relations.

## Current chief justice

The individual currently occupying the distinguished office of Chief Justice is [Richard Wagner](/Richard_Wagner_(judge)). He formally assumed this weighty position on December 18, 2017, taking over from his predecessor, the venerable [Beverley McLachlin](/Beverley_McLachlin). Born in the vibrant city of [Montreal](/Montreal) on April 2, 1957, Justice Wagner brought a wealth of experience to the role, having served as a puisne Supreme Court justice for a considerable 5 years and 74 days before his elevation. Prior to his tenure on the nation's highest court, he honed his judicial acumen on the [Quebec Court of Appeal](/Quebec_Court_of_Appeal), a background that provided him with a deep understanding of both civil and common law traditions, a rather useful prerequisite for the role.

